{
  "texts": [
    "Moreover, 61.5% of tools indexed as 'Red' are fully open-sourced, with publicly available code, weights and training data.",
    "This includes tools with High or Critical misuse-relevant capabilities.",
    "Open-source tools promote innovation and are easier to access for less-resourced researchers and professionals working on biosecurity measures, but publicly-available capabilities are equally accessible to threat actors and cannot be withdrawn once released.",
    "Based on our findings, we recommend five key actions for different stakeholders:",
    "Developers and funders should use the Global Risk Index rubrics to assess tools for misuse-relevant capabilities before funding and developing tools, and before publication and model release."
  ]
}